        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">
        Game over 
        </h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         Before Slack became the go-to workplace communication tool, it was something entirely different—a game.
          </p>
           <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
        Stewart Butterfield, who had previously co-founded the photo-sharing site Flickr (<a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-17-05-2025-sold-to-yahoo" target="_blank">sold to Yahoo for $25M</a>), reunited his original team to launch a startup called Tiny Speck. Their first product was Glitch, a quirky, multiplayer online game Butterfield described as “Monty Python crossed with Dr. Seuss on acid.”
          </p>
           <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         Despite its charm, Glitch failed to attract a large enough user base and became a commercial flop. The game’s foundation, built on Adobe Flash, also restricted its ability to evolve or scale. This was not ideal, especially for a startup that had raised $16M in venture capital.
          </p>
           <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         On December 9, 2012, just 18 months after launch, <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-17-05-2025-glitch-was-shut-down" target="_blank">Glitch was shut down</a>.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         With the company running out of funds, Butterfield offered to return what remained to investors. But then came a bold proposal: instead of calling it quits, why not back one last idea?
          </p>

        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/glitch-game-tiny-speck-stewart-butterfield-slack-founder.png" alt="The game Glitch was developed by Tiny Speck, a company founded by Stewart Butterfield, who also co-founded Flickr and later Slack" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
            The game Glitch was developed by Tiny Speck, a company founded by Stewart Butterfield, who also co-founded Flickr and later Slack. Credits: Tiny Speck</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            Glitch failed to attract the user base needed to sustain it and was a commercial flop. Glitch had other problems too. The game had been built using Adobe Flash, a dying technology that made porting Glitch to modern platforms virtually impossible. Not the most encouraging news when your startup has raised $16M and investor expectations are sky-high.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          When Glitch ceased operations, Tiny Speck was left with just enough funds to provide severance packages to its staff. Butterfield, facing what looked like a failed experiment, made a rather daring proposal: he’d return the funds to investors unless… they wanted to back one more idea.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          While building Glitch, Tiny Speck’s team was scattered across New York, San Francisco, and Vancouver and struggled with communication while working remotely. Frustrated with emails, they relied on <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-17-05-2025-internet-relay-chat" target="_blank">Internet Relay Chat (IRC)</a>. a clunky ’90s protocol that was powerful but archaic. They built a chat tool tailored to their needs to stay on top of Glitch's operations. Need to share a file? Add a feature that does it. Want to search old messages? Build a searchable archive. Tired of messages disappearing? Make it asynchronous.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
