    <mj-column>
      <mj-spacer height="14px" />
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">From Side Project to Slack</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          While building Glitch, the Tiny Speck team spread across New York, San Francisco, and Vancouver, and struggled with remote communication. Tired of chaotic email threads and the clunky interface of IRC (Internet Relay Chat), they built an internal chat tool to manage their work more efficiently.
         </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          This in-house tool allowed them to:
         </p>
         <ul style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6; padding:0px 18px;">
          <li>Share files</li>
          <li>Search conversations</li>
          <li>Keep asynchronous messages visible</li>
         </ul>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          It was not meant to be a product until Glitch failed.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          By early 2013, Butterfield and his team had started refining that internal tool. Their goal? Create an “email killer.” They named it Slack, which stands for Searchable Log of All Conversation and Knowledge.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Slack’s value became obvious. It centralized communication, integrated with tools like Google Drive, Dropbox, Trello, Asana, Salesforce, and even Microsoft Teams, and allowed teams to collaborate in real time. The interface was intuitive, colorful, and playful, echoing Glitch’s design roots. Emojis were everywhere, and they were a hit.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          By March 2013, Tiny Speck was using Slack internally. The team invited other startups to try it out. Feedback poured in, and the product kept improving.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Slack entered beta in 2013 and officially launched in 2014. Adoption was rapid. Its flexibility, seamless integrations, and approachable UI made it a favorite among tech teams.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Tiny Speck rebranded to Slack Technologies in August 2014. <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-17-05-2025-funding" target="_blank">Funding</a> followed quickly:</p>
          <ul style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6; padding:0px 18px;">
          <li>$42.8M in April</li>
          <li>$120M in October</li>
          <li>$160M in 2015</li>
         </ul>
         <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Slack became the fastest-growing SaaS company in history.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          By 2016, it had evolved from a chat tool into a full collaboration suite:</p>
          <ul style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6; padding:0px 18px;">
          <li>Voice calls</li>
          <li>Video conferencing</li>
          <li>Threaded messaging</li>
          <li>Third-party app integrations</li>
         </ul>
         <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Unlike its competitors, Slack offered a robust open tier. Small teams could experience their full potential before ever paying. The premium version unlocked additional storage and deeper integrations.</p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Glitch to glory</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         Slack didn’t just improve workplace chat - it redefined it. It became a central hub for teams, tools, and conversations. Some even called it the “operating system for work.”</p>
         <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         By 2017, Slack had over 8Mn daily users. It raised $200M in April, followed by a $250M round led by SoftBank in September. Its valuation hit $5B.</p>
         </mj-text>

          <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/stewart-butterfield-slack-nyse-ipo-2019.png" alt="Stewart Butterfield, chief executive officer of Slack Technologies Inc., outside the New York Stock Exchange on June 20, 2019, the day of the company’s stock trading debut" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>Stewart Butterfield, chief executive officer of Slack Technologies Inc., outside the New York Stock Exchange on June 20, 2019, the day of the company’s stock trading debut. Credits: Michael Nagle/Bloomberg</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          The key takeaway from Slack’s story?</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <strong>Know when to pivot.</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          If Stewart Butterfield had stuck with Glitch, Slack might not have existed. Recognizing when something isn’t working and having the courage to change direction can make all the difference.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          So if your product is stalling, maybe it’s time to ask some tough, but necessary, questions.</p>
          </mj-text> 
      </mj-column>
